📊 Results Overview

🧬 Cohort Overview

A total of 675 patients were included in this multicentre study of head and neck small round blue cell neoplasms (SRBCNs).

Diagnostic distribution:

Haematolymphoid tumours: 463 cases (68.6%)
Neuroectodermal / neural crest-derived tumours: 84 cases (12.4%)
Mesenchymal tumours: 75 cases (11.1%)
Melanocytic tumours: 53 cases (7.9%)

The cohort comprised 362 males (53.6%) and 313 females (46.4%), with a mean age of 41.8 ± 27.8 years.

At the last follow-up:

435 patients (64.4%) were alive
240 patients (35.6%) had died

🔬 Nuclear Morphometric Analysis

Significant differences were observed across tumour groups for all evaluated nuclear morphometric variables (p < 0.0001).

Tumour Group	Nuclear Area (μm²)	Perimeter (μm)	Circularity	Eccentricity
Haematolymphoid	19.30	19.31	0.767	0.728
Mesenchymal	17.81	17.61	0.783	0.770
Neuroectodermal / Neural Crest	30.40	30.06	0.733	0.751
Melanocytic	23.73	23.36	0.745	0.795

Key findings:

Neuroectodermal/neural crest-derived tumours demonstrated the largest nuclei.
Melanocytic tumours exhibited the highest nuclear eccentricity.
Mesenchymal tumours showed the greatest nuclear circularity.
Haematolymphoid tumours displayed the lowest eccentricity values.

